CripPad open source software in the last 20 years.

00:30.760 --> 00:36.720
So first a bit of a track about myself.

00:36.720 --> 00:44.200
And so I discovered technology in 1984, like using an Apple II and then I moved to PCs,

00:44.200 --> 00:49.200
I even moved to Windows 95, then I graduated from a good school.

00:49.200 --> 00:54.520
And actually in that good school I was kind of told, so I was actually, it was that we

00:54.520 --> 00:59.080
had a speech at some point telling us, you're a soldier of economic war.

00:59.080 --> 01:05.920
And so that of course resonated in a young person, but it also, I mean later on, it's

01:05.920 --> 01:08.680
like what, I mean why are we doing war?

01:08.680 --> 01:10.680
Like that doesn't make any sense.

01:10.680 --> 01:15.360
We're not fighting other countries, we should work together with other countries.

01:15.360 --> 01:21.640
And then in 1995, I was really very interested by the internet.

01:21.640 --> 01:30.440
I saw people using Mozilla browsers, Mosaic browsers in the school and I really just wanted

01:30.440 --> 01:34.200
to work on internet technology.

01:34.200 --> 01:42.280
And I ended up, so I started, I took one job about the internet at Capgemini, but after

01:42.280 --> 01:49.040
a few months I was recruited by Netscape because somebody from the team had left to Netscape

01:49.040 --> 01:51.000
and I ended up working three years.

01:51.000 --> 01:58.280
So who knows Netscape here, like okay, like so just not so bad.

01:58.280 --> 02:02.360
And so I was a consultant, I became also their Mozilla fan.

02:02.360 --> 02:07.120
I even wanted to work for Mozilla, Oregon, inside the company when they launched it.

02:07.120 --> 02:12.640
They didn't take me, so I ended up working in a French startup.

02:12.640 --> 02:19.240
I wanted to stay in Europe and that startup raised money, went IPO.

02:20.000 --> 02:24.880
I actually even was a virtual millionaire and then there was the internet bubble, it

02:24.880 --> 02:25.880
crashed.

02:25.880 --> 02:31.160
I was not at all a millionaire anymore, just like any other IT guy.

02:31.160 --> 02:38.080
And in that company, we were both by US company and in that company I used Wikis and that's

02:38.080 --> 02:44.200
how I wanted, I found Wikis like amazing in terms of how it brings people and helps people

02:44.200 --> 02:46.080
share knowledge.

02:46.080 --> 02:49.000
And that's how in 2004 I created XWiki.

02:49.000 --> 02:54.560
I was a bit accustomed to open source with what Netscape was doing.

02:54.560 --> 03:01.160
Netscape had a highly transparent organization and a way to share things.

03:01.160 --> 03:10.360
It was really pushing internet protocols standards and then they made Mozilla open source.

03:10.360 --> 03:20.640
And then I was a user of open source in my company as a CTO, like installing using Apache

03:20.640 --> 03:23.360
software foundation code and so on.

03:23.360 --> 03:27.360
And so in Wikis, we're purely coming from the open source world.

03:27.360 --> 03:32.080
It was very natural when I wanted to create a company and create a software to create

03:32.080 --> 03:33.080
it as open source.

03:33.080 --> 03:37.000
But I was not as much aware of the political aspects of open source.

03:37.000 --> 03:41.240
I was really looking at open source from the technical point of view.

03:41.240 --> 03:43.680
So that's how I started XWiki.

03:43.680 --> 03:46.880
I'm going to continue from that in this presentation.

03:46.880 --> 03:52.800
But I'm also now a member, our company is a member of APEL, which is an organization

03:52.800 --> 03:56.560
of companies that do open source in Europe.

03:56.560 --> 03:58.800
In France, we have the CNL.

03:58.800 --> 04:01.720
We have the Herb Open Source, OW2.

04:01.720 --> 04:09.440
I'm also on the board of OpenFoodFacts, great association working on open data for food.

04:09.440 --> 04:14.480
And I'm a small shareholder of Morena that is doing an open source phone.

04:14.480 --> 04:16.280
So I'm welcome to look at this.

04:16.280 --> 04:19.120
I find this amazing work.

04:19.120 --> 04:21.600
So what is XWiki SIS?

04:21.600 --> 04:26.120
So XWiki SIS is a French and European independent company.

04:26.120 --> 04:28.400
So it means we've been self-funded.

04:28.400 --> 04:29.840
And I say independent.

04:29.840 --> 04:31.640
It means it's self-funded.

04:31.640 --> 04:34.240
And I still own majority ownership.

04:34.240 --> 04:39.960
And the very large majority of the share is owned by employees, some ex-employees.

